/21/Outlook/Images/DC_Corruption_-0e175.jpg?env=A" data-max-width="4554" data-ratio="1.547" data-title=" " data-uuid="ea097696-b12c-11e3-9627-c65021d6d572"></div><div class="wp-volt-gal-slide wp-volt-gal-photo" data-buy="false" data-caption='MYTH: During the Cold War, we knew who the enemy was. “&lt;span&gt;Throughout the Cold War, fierce disagreements often arose about the nature of the threat,” Mark Kramer writes in “&lt;a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/five-myths-about-the-cold-war/2014/03/13/e8f00f56-a4a5-11e3-84d4-e59b1709222c_story.html"&gt;Five myths about the Cold War&lt;/a&gt;.” “&lt;span&gt;America’s main target changed with the times.” Here, &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt;President Ronald Reagan and first lady Nancy Reagan greet Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev and his wife Raisa outside the White House before a State Dinner in 1987.' data-credit="Ron Edmonds/ASSOCIATED PRESS" data-image="http://www.washingtonpost.com/rw/2010-2019/WashingtonPost/2014/02/07/Style/Images/Gorbachev State Dinner_30_1_2227070700.jpg?env=A" data-max-width="2953" data-ratio="1.474" data-title=" " data-uuid="c8ca80ae-9040-11e3-84e1-27626c5ef5fb"></div><div class="wp-volt-gal-slide wp-volt-gal-photo" data-buy="false" data-caption='MYTH: The SAT predicts college success. “Jesse Rothstein at Stanford University calculates that on its own, the &lt;a data-xslt="_http" href="http://gsppi.berkeley.edu/faculty/jrothstein/published/sat_may03_updated.pdf" target="_blank"&gt;SAT explains&lt;/a&gt; a mere 24 percent of the variation in college freshman grade-point averages,” Anthony P. Carnevale writes in “&lt;a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/five-myths-about-the-sat/2014/03/07/b3b03c4e-a568-11e3-84d4-e59b1709222c_story.html"&gt;Five myths about the SAT&lt;/a&gt;.” “By contrast, high school GPA alone explains 34 percent. Here, Suzane Nazir uses a Princeton Review SAT Preparation book to study for the test in Pembroke Pines, Fla., in March.' data-credit="Joe Raedle/Getty Images" data-image="http://www.washingtonpost.com/rw/2010-2019/WashingtonPost/2014/03/07/Outlook/Images/477028719.jpg?env=A" data-max-width="4688" data-ratio="1.495" data-title=" " data-uuid="a36e8818-a644-11e3-9cff-b1406de784f0"></div><div class="wp-volt-gal-slide wp-volt-gal-photo" data-buy="false" data-caption="MYTH: Winning an Oscar boosts an actor’s career. “Marcia Gay Harden described her best-supporting-actress win to Premiere magazine as ‘disastrous on a professional level,’ because ‘suddenly the parts you’re offered become smaller and the money less,’” Nick Davis writes in “&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/five-myths-about-the-oscars/2014/02/28/c0fa284c-9efb-11e3-b8d8-94577ff66b28_story.html&quot;&gt;Five myths about the Oscars&lt;/a&gt;. “Promising careers often wobble or worse after the big night: Mira Sorvino,&lt;a data-xslt=&quot;_http&quot; href=&quot;http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cnCMqr1QRQw&quot;&gt;Cuba Gooding Jr.&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a data-xslt=&quot;_http&quot; href=&quot;http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8cTR6fk8frs&quot;&gt;Roberto Benigni&lt;/a&gt; , Mercedes Ruehl and Adrien Brody have never gotten film roles equal to those for which they won.” Here, Lupita Nyong'o, a leading best actress nominee for her role in “12 Years a Slave,” in Los Angeles in February." data-credit="Gabriel Olsen/Getty Images" data-image="http://www.washingtonpost.com/rw/2010-2019/WashingtonPost/2014/02/28/Outlook/Images/475240953.jpg?env=A" data-max-width="3000" data-ratio="1.5" data-title=" " data-uuid="a21c42cc-a093-11e3-b8d8-94577ff66b28"></div><div class="wp-volt-gal-slide wp-volt-gal-photo" data-buy="false" data-caption='MYTH: “House of Cards” is Netflix’s first foray into producing content. “&lt;span&gt;Netflix began buying movies — mainly documentaries and low-budget films — in 2004 with ‘Cowboy del Amor’ and the award-winning ‘Born Into Brothels,’” Gina Keating writes in “&lt;a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/five-myths-about-netflix/2014/02/21/787c7c8e-9a3f-11e3-b931-0204122c514b_story.html"&gt;Five myths about Netflix&lt;/a&gt;.” “Content chief Ted Sarandos had a limited budget for his Red Envelope Entertainment, and he used it to ally Netflix with the burgeoning independent-film community.&lt;/span&gt;” Here, Kevin Spacey as Francis Underwood, left, and Robin Wright as Clair Underwood in a scene from "House of Cards." ' data-credit="Nathaniel E. Bell/AP" data-image="http://www.washingtonpost.com/rw/2010-2019/WashingtonPost/2014/02/21/Outlook/Images/Online-House_of_Cards-0d2a0.jpg?env=A" data-max-width="3147" data-ratio="1.499" data-title=" " data-uuid="dec61e56-9b47-11e3-975d-107dfef7b668"></div><div class="wp-volt-gal-slide wp-volt-gal-photo" data-buy="false" data-caption='MYTH: You know what you’re getting when you get a purebred dog. “As with people and every other animal, the genome interacts with the environment to create the individual,” Alexandra Horowitz writes in “&lt;a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/five-myths-about-dogs/2014/02/10/c53c6970-8f46-11e3-b46a-5a3d0d2130da_story.html" title="www.washingtonpost.com"&gt;Five myths about dogs&lt;/a&gt;.” “A timid golden retriever puppy who gets out of a fearful encounter by biting could learn to become a regular biter of anyone who approaches suddenly.” Here, a Briard named "Cagney" at the Westminster Dog Show in New York City. ' data-credit="Andrew Burton/Getty Images" data-image="http://www.washingtonpost.com/rw/2010-2019/WashingtonPost/2014/02/11/Outlook/Images/468363665-590.jpg?env=A" data-max-width="3000" data-ratio="1.5" data-title=" " data-uuid="0570a548-9356-11e3-83b9-1f024193bb84"></div><div class="wp-volt-gal-slide wp-volt-gal-photo" data-buy="false" data-caption='MYTH: Bob Dylan’s Super Bowl ad for Chrysler makes him a sellout. “If his Chrysler ad makes him a sellout, he sold out long ago,” writes Elizabeth Thomson in “&lt;a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/five-myths-about-bob-dylan/2014/02/07/20ed